stalment) ÷ Income × 100%.</p></li><li data-start="2062" data-end="2137"><p data-start="2065" data-end="2137"><strong data-start="2065" data-end="2080">Loan Tenure</strong> – Longer tenure = smaller instalment, easier approval.</p></li><li data-start="2138" data-end="2203"><p data-start="2141" data-end="2203"><strong data-start="2141" data-end="2158">Interest Rate</strong> – Lower rate = more affordable instalment.</p></li><li data-start="2204" data-end="2279"><p data-start="2207" data-end="2279"><strong data-start="2207" data-end="2226">Age of Borrower</strong> – Most banks require full repayment before age 70.</p></li><li data-start="2280" data-end="2358"><p data-start="2283" data-end="2358"><strong data-start="2283" data-end="2301">Credit History</strong> – CCRIS / CTOS report must show good repayment habits.</p></li><li data-start="2359" data-end="2476"><p data-start="2362" data-end="2476"><strong data-start="2362" data-end="2390">Property Type &amp; Location</strong> – Certain banks may impose conditions on sub-sale or under-construction properties.</p></li></ol><hr data-start="2478" data-end="2481" /><h2 data-start="2483" data-end="2526">🏦 Typical Bank DSR Limits in Malaysia</h2><ul data-start="2528" data-end="2820"><li data-start="2528" data-end="2612"><p data-start="2530" data-end="2612"><strong data-start="2530" data-end="2598">Conventional banks (Maybank, CIMB, Public Bank, Hong Leong, RHB)</strong> → ~45% cap.</p></li><li data-start="2613" data-end="2675"><p data-start="2615" data-end="2675"><strong data-start="2615" data-end="2642">Higher income borrowers</strong> → Sometimes allowed up to 60%.</p></li><li data-start="2676" data-end="2820"><p data-start="2678" data-end="2820"><strong data-start="2678" data-end="2713">Public sector (LPPSA financing)</strong> → Monthly commitments cannot exceed 60% of gross income; total debt usually capped at 80% of net income.</p></li></ul><hr data-start="2822" data-end="2825" /><h2 data-start="2827" data-end="2877">💡 Government &amp; Special Schemes for Full Loan</h2><p data-start="2879" data-end="2960">Malaysia offers several schemes that let you apply for a <strong data-start="2936" data-end="2957">full loan or more</strong>:</p><ul data-start="2962" data-end="3417"><li data-start="2962" data-end="3068"><p data-start="2964" data-end="3068"><strong data-start="2964" data-end="3004">SJKP (Skim Jaminan Kredit Perumahan)</strong> → Up to <strong data-start="3013" data-end="3031">110% financing</strong> (covers loan + MRTA + legal fees).</p></li><li data-start="3069" data-end="3147"><p data-start="3071" data-end="3147"><strong data-start="3071" data-end="3086">SJKP MADANI</strong> → Up to <strong data-start="3095" data-end="3113">120% financing</strong> for eligible first-time buyers.</p></li><li data-start="3148" data-end="3255"><p data-start="3150" data-end="3255"><strong data-start="3150" data-end="3184">My First Home Scheme (RUMAWIP)</strong> → Special programme for properties up to RM500k with 100% financing.</p></li><li data-start="3256" data-end="3417"><p data-start="3258" data-end="3417"><strong data-start="3258" data-end="3283">Stamp Duty Exemptions</strong> → First-time buyers enjoy <strong data-start="3310" data-end="3341">full exemption up to RM500k</strong> and <strong data-start="3346" data-end="3385">50% exemption between RM500k – RM1m</strong> (subject to Budget policies).</p></li></ul><hr data-start="3419" data-end="3422" /><h2 data-start="3424" data-end="3471">📑 Documents Required for Loan Application</h2><p data-start="3473" data-end="3524">To apply for a housing loan in Malaysia, prepare:</p><ul data-start="3526" data-end="3768"><li data-start="3526" data-end="3542"><p data-start="3528" data-end="3542">NRIC / MyKad</p></li><li data-start="3543" data-end="3571"><p data-start="3545" data-end="3571">Latest 3 months payslips</p></li><li data-start="3572" data-end="3607"><p data-start="3574" data-end="3607">Latest 6 months bank statements</p></li><li data-start="3608" 